1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,312
What if everything you learned about
Rome's fall was wrong?

2
00:00:04,312 --> 00:00:09,500
Today, we uncover the truth that
historians have debated for centuries.

3
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:14,537
The Roman Empire didn't fall in a day.

4
00:00:14,537 --> 00:00:26,070
For over three hundred years, it slowly
crumbled under the weight of its own
ambitions.

5
00:00:26,070 --> 00:00:38,000
Economic collapse, military overextension,
and political corruption all played their
part.

6
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,909
Let's start with the economy.

7
00:00:41,909 --> 00:00:48,109
By the third century, Rome was bleeding
money.

8
00:00:48,109 --> 00:00:55,791
The cost of maintaining a vast army
drained the treasury.

9
00:00:55,791 --> 00:01:09,000
Emperors debased the currency, flooding
the market with coins that contained less
and less silver.

10
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:13,245
Then came the military crisis.

11
00:01:13,245 --> 00:01:30,792
Rome's legions, once the most feared
fighting force in the world, were
stretched thin across thousands of miles
of frontier.

12
00:01:30,792 --> 00:01:34,472
Barbarian raids increased.

13
00:01:34,472 --> 00:01:39,000
The empire struggled to respond.

14
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:43,580
Political chaos made everything worse.

15
00:01:43,580 --> 00:01:49,607
In just fifty years, Rome had over fifty
emperors.

16
00:01:49,607 --> 00:01:52,379
Most were assassinated.

17
00:01:52,379 --> 00:01:55,754
Stability became impossible.

18
00:01:55,754 --> 00:02:06,000
The Senate lost its authority, and the
rule of law gave way to the rule of the
sword.

19
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:19,527
And yet, the Eastern Roman Empire survived
for another thousand years.

20
00:02:19,527 --> 00:02:28,995
This tells us that Rome's fall wasn't
inevitable.

21
00:02:28,995 --> 00:02:46,000
It was the result of specific choices made
by specific people in specific
circumstances.

22
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:49,918
That's the lesson history teaches us.

23
00:02:49,918 --> 00:02:54,894
Great civilizations don't fall because of
fate.

24
00:02:54,894 --> 00:02:58,176
They fall because of decisions.

25
00:02:58,176 --> 00:03:04,000
And that's a lesson we would do well to
remember today.

26
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:11,576
If you found this video valuable, hit the
like button and subscribe for more history
that challenges what you think you know.

27
00:03:11,576 --> 00:03:14,303
What do you think was Rome's biggest
mistake?

28
00:03:14,303 --> 00:03:16,000
Let us know in the comments.
